  "content": "# Top 20 Things to Know About Claude Code\n\n---\n\n## 1. It's an Agentic Coding Assistant\nClaude Code is Anthropic's AI-powered coding tool that reads your **entire codebase**, edits multiple files, runs terminal commands, and integrates with your dev tools. It's like having an AI pair programmer that understands your whole project and executes changes autonomously.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Available on Every Surface\n- **CLI** â€” Full-featured terminal experience\n- **VS Code** â€” Extension with inline diffs & @-mentions\n- **JetBrains** â€” IntelliJ, PyCharm, WebStorm plugin\n- **Desktop App** â€” Mac & Windows with visual diff review\n- **Web** â€” claude.ai/code, no local setup needed\n- **Mobile** â€” Send tasks from the Claude iOS app\n\nSessions sync across all surfaces.\n\n---\n\n## 3. One-Command Install\n```bash\n# macOS / Linux\ncurl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | sh\n# Windows\nwinget install Anthropic.ClaudeCode\n# npm\nnpm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\n```\nNative installs auto-update in the background.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Git Integration Is First-Class\nClaude works directly with git â€” stages changes, writes descriptive commit messages, creates branches, opens PRs with context-aware descriptions, and supports **git worktrees** for parallel isolated sessions.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Multi-File Editing\nAtomic edits across your entire project. Claude understands how changes in one file ripple through others â€” refactors, renames, and dependency updates handled seamlessly.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Essential Slash Commands\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---------|--------|\n| `/help` | Built-in docs |\n| `/commit` | Smart commits |\n| `/review` | Code review |\n| `/compact` | Free context space |\n| `/memory` | View/edit CLAUDE.md |\n| `/model` | Switch models |\n| `/plan` | Enter plan mode |\n| `/hooks` | Lifecycle hooks |\n| `/mcp` | External tools |\n| `/agents` | Manage subagents |\n| `/effort` | Reasoning depth |\n| `/loop` | Recurring tasks |\n\n---\n\n## 7. CLAUDE.md â€” Persistent Project Memory\nCommit a `CLAUDE.md` to your repo with coding standards, architecture decisions, preferred libraries, and build commands. Claude reads it **every session** automatically. Create one with `/init`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Auto Memory\nClaude **self-learns** without you writing anything â€” saves build commands, code style preferences, debugging insights, and architecture notes to `~/.claude/projects/<project>/memory/MEMORY.md`. Toggle with `/memory`.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Hooks System\nAutomate actions at lifecycle points (`SessionStart`, `PreToolUse`, `PostToolUse`, `Stop`):\n- Auto-format code after edits (Prettier/ESLint)\n- Block edits to protected files\n- Send notifications when Claude needs input\n- Audit configuration changes\n\nConfigured in `settings.json` with fine-grained matchers.\n\n---\n\n## 10. MCP â€” Connect 100+ External Tools\nModel Context Protocol connects Claude to GitHub, Slack, Jira, PostgreSQL, Google Drive, Sentry, and more. Add servers in `.mcp.json` â€” Claude auto-discovers and uses them contextually.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Six Permission Modes\n| Mode | Behavior |\n|------|----------|\n| `default` | Ask before each action |\n| `acceptEdits` | Auto-approve file edits |\n| `plan` | Show plan first |\n| `auto` | Background safety checks |\n| `dontAsk` | Pre-approved tools (CI) |\n| `bypassPermissions` | No prompts (sandboxed only) |\n\nSwitch mid-session with **Shift+Tab**.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Extended Thinking & Adaptive Reasoning\nEnabled by default â€” Claude reasons internally before responding. Supports effort levels (low â†’ max). Use `/effort` to adjust, or say *\"ultrathink\"* for one-off deep reasoning. View thinking with `Ctrl+O`.\n\n---\n\n## 13. Subagents â€” Specialized AI Teammates\nDedicated agents for code review, debugging, data science, and more â€” each with its own context window. Create custom agents in `.claude/agents/` with YAML frontmatter. Claude auto-delegates matching tasks.\n\n---\n\n## 14. Context Window Management\nYour context fills as you work. Manage it:\n- **`/compact`** â€” Summarize conversation to free space\n- **Subagents** â€” Offload tasks to separate windows\n- **Worktrees** â€” `claude --worktree` for isolation\n- **`--bare`** â€” Skip extras for lean CI runs\n- Watch the **context indicator** in the prompt bar\n\n---\n\n## 15. Headless / Non-Interactive Mode\nPerfect for scripts and CI/CD:\n```bash\nclaude -p \"fix all lint errors\" \\\n  --allowedTools \"Bash,Read,Edit\" \\\n  --output-format json \\\n  --permission-mode dontAsk\n```\nCapture structured output, chain with other tools.\n\n---\n\n## 16. IDE Integrations\n**VS Code**: Graphical panel, inline diffs, @-mentions, plan review, conversation tabs, drag-to-reposition.\n\n**JetBrains**: IntelliJ, PyCharm, WebStorm â€” interactive diff viewing, context sharing.\n\nBoth share settings with CLI via `~/.claude/settings.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 17. Model Selection\nUse aliases: `sonnet`, `opus`, `haiku`. Set with `/model`, `--model`, or `ANTHROPIC_MODEL`.\n\n- **`opusplan`** â€” Opus for planning, Sonnet for execution\n- **1M context window** on Opus 4.6 & Sonnet 4.6\n- **Fast mode** â€” Same model, faster output (`/fast`)\n\n---\n\n## 18. Agent SDK\nBuild your own agents with the **Claude Agent SDK** (Python & TypeScript). Full control over tools, permissions, sessions, structured outputs, and cost tracking. Use in scripts, web apps, or internal tools.\n\n---\n\n## 19. Session Management\nNever lose your work:\n- `claude --continue` â€” Resume most recent session\n- `claude --resume name` â€” Resume by name\n- `claude -n \"feature-x\"` â€” Name sessions at startup\n- **Checkpoints** â€” Rewind, fork, or revert changes\n- **Worktrees** â€” Parallel isolated sessions\n\n---\n\n## 20. Unix Philosophy â€” Composable & Pipeable\n```bash\n# Pipe logs for analysis\ntail -200 app.log | claude -p \"summarize errors\"\n\n# Review a diff\ngit diff | claude -p \"review this diff\"\n\n# Automate with cron\nclaude -p \"run tests and fix failures\" --bare\n```\n\n---\n\n> **Pro Tip:** Start every project with `/init` to create a `CLAUDE.md`, then use `/memory` to see what Claude has learned about your codebase over time.\n\n---\n\n*Generated April 2026 â€” Claude Code (Opus 4.6)*"
